  "prompt": "What is the maximum number of tabs open in Google or Computer?",
  "response": "The maximum number of tabs you can open in Google Chrome or on a computer can vary depending on several factors, including the amount of RAM your computer has, the processing power, and the specific browser you are using.\n\nFor Google Chrome specifically, there isn't a hard limit imposed by the browser itself. However, performance issues can arise as you open more tabs. Users typically start experiencing slowdowns when they have several dozen tabs open, depending on their system's capabilities. In practice, users have reported opening hundreds of tabs, but this is not advisable due to significant performance degradation.\n\nFor other browsers or general computer use, similar principles apply: the more tabs or applications you have open, the more system resources are consumed, potentially leading to slow performance or crashes.\n\nIn summary, while there isn't a strict maximum number imposed by the software, the practical limit is determined by your computer's hardware and performance characteristics.",
